1: Load and prepare data

The selected exposure list is loaded for later visualisation:

MR result data is loaded:

mr.res <- fread("~/bio/code/mpip/dex-stim-human-array/output/data/integrative/phewas/10_cell_type_groups/mr_results_clumped.rds")

2 Processing

2.1 Annotation

Results are annotated in multiple steps.

First, information on traits and batches are merged back from the selected exposures file:

Clean extra hyphen from batch data:

The exposure.group variable is recoded with proper names:

The CpG column is created based on the exposure label:

mr.res.ao$cpg <- unlist(strsplit(mr.res.ao$exposure, "_"))[seq(from = 4, to = 2*nrow(mr.res.ao), by = 4)]

The number of phenotypes analysed per batch is as follows:

Overall, there is no indication that there are more PheWAS hits in any of the exposure groups:

chisq.test(sig.table)


    Pearson's Chi-squared test

data:  sig.table

Second, FDR-corrected significant results are exported and saved:

nrow(mr.res.ao.fdr.sig)

[1] 246

These results are annotated manually to group outcome traits. Annotated data are read back in and categories shown in a frequency table:

table(mr.res.ao.fdr.sig$trait_category)


       Biomarker  Body morphology          Disease    Immune system Neuro-behavioral        Nutrition 
              70               37               69               50                5                1 
           Other 
              14

The respective distributions are visualised in a bar chart:

2.2: Most frequent traits

The most frequently observed outcome traits across the individual functional groups are as follows:

mr.res.ao.fdr.sig %>%
   group_by(exposure.group, trait) %>%
   summarize(n_trait = n()) %>%
   arrange(desc(n_trait)) %>%
   filter(trait %in% head(trait, 5)) %>%
   ungroup() %>%
   mutate(trait = factor(trait, levels = rev(unique(trait)))) %>%
   ggplot(aes(x = trait, y = n_trait)) +
   geom_bar(aes(fill = exposure.group), stat = "identity", col = "black",
            position = position_dodge()) +
   facet_wrap(.~exposure.group) +
   labs(x = "", y = "No. of FDR-corrected associations") +
   scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set2") +
   coord_flip() +
   theme_bw() +
   theme(legend.position = "none",
         legend.title = element_blank(),
         legend.background = element_blank(),
         plot.background = element_blank())

`summarise()` has grouped output by 'exposure.group'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

2.3 Visualisation data

Visualisation data for the Shiny app is created using a subset of relevant columns from mr_res:

vis_dat = mr.res.ao.fdr.sig %>%
   select(exposure.group, exposure, SNP, trait, batch, outcome, samplesize, b, se, p, fdr)

The exposure variable is shortened by removing the exposure.group id:

The trait category is merged from the FDR hits:

vis_dat = left_join(vis_dat, mr_res_fdrsig[, c("exposure.group", "SNP", "outcome", "trait_category")],
                    by = c("exposure.group" = "exposure.group", "SNP" = "SNP", "outcome" = "outcome"))

Error in is.data.frame(y) : object 'mr_res_fdrsig' not found

The p-value column is corrected to exchange all exact 0s with Rs lowest number to avoid computational errors:

A new P-value column is created for -log10(P) values as well as the same variable with valence information from betas added:

vis_dat$pval_log10 = -log10(vis_dat$p)
vis_dat$pval_log10_val = ifelse(vis_dat$b > 0, vis_dat$pval_log10, -vis_dat$pval_log10)

Traits are recoded to obtain proper names and data arranged by batch.label:

vis_dat = arrange(vis_dat, desc(outcome), batch, trait)
vis_dat$trait = factor(vis_dat$trait, levels = unique(vis_dat$trait))

Data is saved again for creation of the Shiny app:
